WEBVTT

0
00:00:00.009 --> 00:00:00.409
All right,

1
00:00:00.569 --> 00:00:00.889
welcome.

2
00:00:01.169 --> 00:00:03.329
Today we are diving deep into a document

3
00:00:03.329 --> 00:00:05.869
that can absolutely transform your investment committee.

4
00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:08.270
We're talking about the investment committee charter.

5
00:00:08.409 --> 00:00:09.510
Let's get right into it.

6
00:00:10.050 --> 00:00:12.359
So let's just start with a really critical question.

7
00:00:12.529 --> 00:00:14.949
Something every board member has to ask themselves.

8
00:00:15.210 --> 00:00:16.469
When the stakes are highest,

9
00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:18.440
what is really driving your decisions?

10
00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:19.290
Is it cold,

11
00:00:19.329 --> 00:00:20.030
hard data,

12
00:00:20.209 --> 00:00:24.000
or is it the invisible and frankly powerful pull of human psychology?

13
00:00:24.290 --> 00:00:25.989
That's the core challenge we're going to tackle today.

14
00:00:26.719 --> 00:00:27.049
OK,

15
00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:28.120
here's our game plan.

16
00:00:28.409 --> 00:00:28.649
First,

17
00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:31.520
we'll look at just how high stakes capital decisions are.

18
00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:35.520
Then we'll introduce the charter as your blueprint for solid governance.

19
00:00:35.919 --> 00:00:36.290
After that,

20
00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:39.240
we'll get into the nitty gritty of structuring your committee for success,

21
00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:41.340
making sure transitions are seamless,

22
00:00:41.529 --> 00:00:42.200
and finally,

23
00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:45.250
figuring out how to measure if it's all actually working.

24
00:00:46.020 --> 00:00:49.150
To really appreciate why a charter is so crucial,

25
00:00:49.349 --> 00:00:52.299
you first have to understand the environment you're operating in.

26
00:00:52.509 --> 00:00:52.819
I mean,

27
00:00:52.950 --> 00:00:57.020
the world of major capital investment is a minefield of both financial risk and,

28
00:00:57.189 --> 00:00:57.540
you know,

29
00:00:57.750 --> 00:00:58.970
psychological traps.

30
00:00:59.560 --> 00:00:59.909
Look,

31
00:01:00.029 --> 00:01:01.750
the decisions your committee makes,

32
00:01:01.990 --> 00:01:03.470
these are not small bets.

33
00:01:03.669 --> 00:01:06.309
We're talking about massive amounts of money being poured

34
00:01:06.309 --> 00:01:08.690
into projects that once you pull the trigger,

35
00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:11.040
are almost impossible to reverse.

36
00:01:11.269 --> 00:01:13.599
A mistake here isn't just a bad quarter.

37
00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:17.910
It can literally define your company's path for the next 5 or 10 years.

38
00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:19.800
But the financial risk,

39
00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:21.279
that's only half the story.

40
00:01:21.449 --> 00:01:23.449
The other half is the invisible enemy,

41
00:01:23.569 --> 00:01:24.639
our own minds.

42
00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:25.769
Even the smartest,

43
00:01:25.889 --> 00:01:28.360
most experienced leaders fall into these traps.

44
00:01:28.610 --> 00:01:30.949
You've got overconfidence making you feel invincible

45
00:01:31.139 --> 00:01:32.139
or anchoring bias,

46
00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:35.480
where the first number you hear suddenly becomes the only number that matters.

47
00:01:35.849 --> 00:01:36.970
These aren't character flaws.

48
00:01:37.089 --> 00:01:39.089
They're just predictable glitches in human software

49
00:01:39.089 --> 00:01:40.730
that you have to build defenses against.

50
00:01:41.339 --> 00:01:44.940
And here is what happens when those biases are left to run wild.

51
00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:47.860
This quote from a portfolio manager just nails it.

52
00:01:48.139 --> 00:01:49.250
Without a real process,

53
00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:52.080
it all breaks down into a contest of wills.

54
00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:54.529
It becomes about who has the most influence,

55
00:01:54.699 --> 00:01:56.379
who's the best politician in the room.

56
00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:57.690
The loudest voice wins,

57
00:01:57.699 --> 00:01:59.580
not necessarily the best idea.

58
00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:02.440
So how do you protect against all that?

59
00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:05.970
How do you put up guardrails against subjectivity and pure emotion?

60
00:02:06.250 --> 00:02:06.410
Well,

61
00:02:06.489 --> 00:02:08.929
the answer lies in one powerful document.

62
00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:11.369
This is your foundation for success.

63
00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:14.940
And that solution is the Investment Committee charter.

64
00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:18.419
I want you to think of it as the Constitution for your committee.

65
00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:21.110
Its job isn't to say what you should invest in,

66
00:02:21.320 --> 00:02:23.470
but to lay out how you will govern yourselves,

67
00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:25.149
how you'll make decisions,

68
00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:26.759
and how you'll stay accountable.

69
00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:30.500
It's the rulebook that ensures every idea gets a fair hearing.

70
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:31.149
Now,

71
00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:35.589
this is a really important distinction because people mix these two up all the time.

72
00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:39.880
The charter is not the same as the investment policy statement or IPS.

73
00:02:40.229 --> 00:02:41.210
Let me make it simple.

74
00:02:41.429 --> 00:02:44.009
The charter governs the people and the process.

75
00:02:44.229 --> 00:02:46.779
The IPS governs the portfolio and the money.

76
00:02:46.990 --> 00:02:48.210
You need both for sure,

77
00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:49.949
but the charter has to come first.

78
00:02:50.029 --> 00:02:51.070
It's the foundation.

79
00:02:51.589 --> 00:02:54.750
So what actually goes into a really effective charter?

80
00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:55.270
Well,

81
00:02:55.339 --> 00:02:57.130
it covers all these key areas.

82
00:02:57.229 --> 00:03:01.410
It forces you to get crystal clear on everything from why these assets even exist

83
00:03:01.589 --> 00:03:03.000
to the rules for running a meeting.

84
00:03:03.259 --> 00:03:04.429
And by spelling out rules,

85
00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:06.309
fiduciary duties and term limits,

86
00:03:06.389 --> 00:03:07.729
you eliminate ambiguity.

87
00:03:07.949 --> 00:03:10.250
Everyone knows exactly what's expected of them,

88
00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:12.929
which builds a true culture of accountability.

89
00:03:13.389 --> 00:03:13.669
OK,

90
00:03:13.789 --> 00:03:16.789
let's drill down on one of those components that might seem small,

91
00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:17.550
but believe me,

92
00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:20.630
it has a huge impact on how effective your committee is,

93
00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:21.869
and that's its size.

94
00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:26.809
Years of experience and research have shown us there is a definite sweet spot.

95
00:03:27.059 --> 00:03:29.139
The ideal number of members for an investment

96
00:03:29.139 --> 00:03:31.559
committee is somewhere between 5 and 8.

97
00:03:31.899 --> 00:03:34.130
That range is big enough to get diverse perspectives,

98
00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:37.899
but it's small enough that you can still be agile and actually make a decision.

99
00:03:38.490 --> 00:03:40.119
And if you get this number wrong,

100
00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:41.970
you are just asking for trouble.

101
00:03:42.169 --> 00:03:43.130
If you go too small,

102
00:03:43.210 --> 00:03:45.110
you might struggle to even get a vote,

103
00:03:45.130 --> 00:03:46.919
and you're at high risk of groupthink.

104
00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:49.679
Go too large and the whole thing bogs down.

105
00:03:49.889 --> 00:03:51.080
Discussions take forever,

106
00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:52.529
people don't get a chance to speak,

107
00:03:52.559 --> 00:03:54.770
and decisions get kicked down the road again and again.

108
00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:57.610
And this isn't just some academic theory.

109
00:03:57.860 --> 00:03:59.330
Here's a real world example.

110
00:03:59.619 --> 00:04:02.820
There was a committee with 12 members and they were basically paralyzed.

111
00:04:03.139 --> 00:04:04.169
Meetings would drag on,

112
00:04:04.419 --> 00:04:06.020
key decisions were always deferred,

113
00:04:06.179 --> 00:04:08.220
and they couldn't even get through their own agenda.

114
00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:10.419
Their size wasn't just a detail,

115
00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:11.699
it was their destiny.

116
00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:14.600
So you've got the right number of people on the bus.

117
00:04:14.839 --> 00:04:15.300
Great.

118
00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:16.950
But people don't stay forever.

119
00:04:17.178 --> 00:04:18.420
Members change.

120
00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:22.100
And that brings up one of the single biggest long-term risks you face,

121
00:04:22.359 --> 00:04:25.160
losing that priceless institutional knowledge every

122
00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:26.390
time someone walks out the door.

123
00:04:26.790 --> 00:04:30.140
This is where your charter becomes your absolute best friend

124
00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:32.029
by setting formal term limits,

125
00:04:32.109 --> 00:04:33.850
and we recommend at least 5 years,

126
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.279
and then staggering those terms,

127
00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:36.709
you don't have everyone leaving at once.

128
00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:38.260
You create a bridge.

129
00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:40.519
You're passing knowledge from one group to the next.

130
00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:43.779
That rule about rotating less than a third of the committee at a time,

131
00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:45.089
that is gold.

132
00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:47.570
It's a fantastic guardrail against chaos.

133
00:04:47.989 --> 00:04:51.089
And if you want to see the real world cost of getting this wrong,

134
00:04:51.510 --> 00:04:52.570
just listen to this.

135
00:04:52.869 --> 00:04:55.029
A big group of new members came in and

136
00:04:55.029 --> 00:04:58.549
they just didn't understand a complex long-term private investment.

137
00:04:58.910 --> 00:04:59.619
So what they do,

138
00:04:59.790 --> 00:05:00.630
they paused it,

139
00:05:00.809 --> 00:05:04.100
and that one decision directly hurt the fund's returns.

140
00:05:04.429 --> 00:05:07.070
That is precisely the kind of self-inflicted wound

141
00:05:07.070 --> 00:05:09.149
a well-written charter is designed to prevent.

142
00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:09.899
OK,

143
00:05:10.010 --> 00:05:10.880
let's bring it home.

144
00:05:11.019 --> 00:05:12.869
Let's talk about performance,

145
00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.600
because a bright charter isn't just about avoiding disaster,

146
00:05:15.779 --> 00:05:18.480
it's about actively engineering success.

147
00:05:18.779 --> 00:05:20.500
How do you make sure the committee isn't just busy,

148
00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:22.720
but is actually effective for the long haul?

149
00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:25.459
The charter itself becomes your scorecard.

150
00:05:25.779 --> 00:05:28.380
It forces you to define what success even looks like.

151
00:05:28.570 --> 00:05:30.619
It clarifies who's accountable for what,

152
00:05:30.739 --> 00:05:31.959
so there's no finger pointing.

153
00:05:32.140 --> 00:05:34.679
It standardizes your process for consistency

154
00:05:34.899 --> 00:05:38.260
and it puts your fiduciary duty right there in black and white,

155
00:05:38.459 --> 00:05:41.500
making it the bedrock of every single conversation.

156
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.670
And that leads us to probably the most important takeaway of all.

157
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.739
Your charter can't be a set it and forget it document.

158
00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:49.920
It's not something you write,

159
00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:51.940
file away and never look at again.

160
00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:53.670
It has to be a living,

161
00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:54.859
breathing blueprint

162
00:05:54.959 --> 00:05:55.540
that you use,

163
00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:56.679
that you review,

164
00:05:56.839 --> 00:05:58.380
and that you refine over time.

165
00:05:58.579 --> 00:06:01.820
It is your single best tool for creating long-term stability.

166
00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:04.299
So that brings us to our final question,

167
00:06:04.559 --> 00:06:07.089
and this is one for you to take back to your own board.

168
00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:11.769
Is your charter a living document that's actively guiding your biggest decisions,

169
00:06:12.059 --> 00:06:14.250
or is it a relic sitting in a binder,

170
00:06:14.299 --> 00:06:15.890
gathering dust on a shelf?

171
00:06:16.339 --> 00:06:17.760
Because the answer to that question

172
00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.660
tells you pretty much everything you need to

173
00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:22.239
know about the future stability of your investments.